			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">the easiest way of looking at it is that /pet hold is an extension of /pet back off. the difference being with /pet hold it wont react if attacked. as with /pet back off your pet will go back to doing whatever its last non /pet attack command it had prior, but it just wont react if attacked and will just stay there. if your pet was on follow it will go back to following you, if pet was guarded  will go back to its guard spot etc etc. 
<br />

<br />
and as someone stated i have /pet back off after all my /pet hold commands to ensure the hate list and stuff like that is clear. i learned this in CT where there is horrible problems with pet mez breaks and holding a pet, reattacking it on main target and watching pet shoot for its last wrong target. i would suggest everyone to do this. as well i have a follow hotkey /pet hold /pet back off /pet follow which is also good for repositioning during fights. with new pet messages filter its not really a problem with spam though i used to get tells that my pet talked too much and was seemingly too obedient and could i please use my hotkeys less <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="Razz" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
if you plan on raiding its a MUST have, if you dong plan on raiding its still invaluable and reduces many of those annoying moments where you look like an idiot because you either cant control pet or are spaming back off. every bst should get it
<br />

<br />
oh and for the multiple mob senario. pet hold wont be a magic command to lock the pet on one particular mob, it will however make repositioning MUCH MUCH easier and you'll waste alot less time. just hit pet hold, hit follow, take several steps back if you have to to get all mobs rebunched, resend pet and circle around to other side. you again have pet on same mob and hitting from back. 
<br />

<br />
wow i look like a tool writing so much about the /pet hold command, its just that essential as i dont trust a pet class without it</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
