			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">If you were making a key for your pet, I would not use 
<br />

<br />
/pet hold
<br />
/pet backoff
<br />

<br />
in that order.  Yes, pet hold tells your pet to not attack anything even if the pet or yourself are under attack thru melee or spells.  Yes, pet backoff does the same thing as pet hold with exception.  If at any time after you hit the /pet backoff key and you or your pet takes any kind of damage, weither its melee, dot, or dd your pet will assume attacking the mob unless the mob on your pet's agro list is already dead.  However, as you move around, any damage you or your pet takes, will cause your pet to attack whatever caused the damage.
<br />

<br />
The point of having /pet hold is to remove your pet from combat all together.  Prominate use is on raids where there is a potential of AOE casting mobs and you are not suppose to attack or assist with your pet until told to do so.  With pet backoff being the last command sent to your pet, any immediate damage done to you or your pet will cause your pet to attack whatever caused the damage to it.  
<br />

<br />
What I do is this. 
<br />

<br />
1. Keep the pet parked near you but out of the way of incoming mobs/pulls.
<br />

<br />
/pet guard here
<br />
/pet hold
<br />

<br />
2. When a mob is incoming, if a mob hits me or does any damage to me or pet, the pet will not attack incoming mob, until I tell pet.
<br />

<br />
/pet attack
<br />

<br />
3. If I am told to get pet off or after the fight is over, I tell pet to go back to its guard spot, 
<br />

<br />
/pet hold
<br />

<br />
4. Unless we are going to move.
<br />

<br />
/pet hold
<br />
/pet back off
<br />

<br />
/pet follow
<br />
/pet hold
<br />

<br />
This will keep pet from attacking anything, clear its agro list, and then not attack anything while we are relocating camp.
<br />

<br />
When I get to the new spot where we are killing, I repeat the steps above.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
